red form of   Cheney   3. Altered ending reflects the Canadian and American French practice of sounding the final <i>-t</i>.","History: The (majority of the) Chenettes are descendants of Bertrand Chesnay/Chenay <i>dit</i>/<i>sieur</i> de La Garenne from Brittany (France); see   Cheney  ."]},{"name":"Chaney","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): habitational name from any one of several places in Normandy, Picardy, or Artois (France) named (Le) Quesnay or Quesnoy, or elsewhere in northern France named (Le or La) Chesnay or Chesnoy. The placenames all derive from Old French <i>chesnai</i> or its Normanno-Picard equivalent <i>quesnai</i> ‘oak grove’ (medieval Latin <i>casnetum</i>).","French: variant of <b>Chanet</b>, a habitational name from any of various places called Chanet or Le Chanet, from Latin <i>canna</i> ‘reed’ + the suffix <i>-etum</i> denoting an inhabitant."]}]},{"name":"Elizabeth","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["The usual spelling of   Elisabeth   in English. It is recorded in the medieval period, but was made popular by being borne by  Queen Elizabeth I  of England (  1533–1603 ). In the 20th century it again became extremely fashionable, partly because it was the name of  Elizabeth Bowes-Lyon  (  1900–2002 ), who in  1936  became Queen Elizabeth as the wife of King George VI, and after his death in  1952  achieved great public affection as Queen Mother for nearly half a century. Even more influentially, it is the name of her daughter  Queen Elizabeth II  (  b. 1926 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Elisabeth","meanings":["The spelling of   Elizabeth   used in the Authorized Version of the New Testament, and in most modern European languages. This was the name of the mother of John the Baptist (Luke 1:60). Etymologically, the name means ‘God is my oath’, and is therefore identical with <i>Elisheba</i>, the name of the wife of Aaron according to the genealogy at Exodus 6:23. The final element seems to have been altered by association with Hebrew <i>shabbāth</i> ‘Sabbath’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Elizabeth Cheney was born in 1285, in Northumberland, England, United Kingdom. She married Robert Fitzralph Lawson in 1299, in Bywell St Andrew, Northumberland, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1285–":"1285–Surnud","1280–Male":"1280–Surnud","1300–1385":"1300–1385","1285–Female":"1285–Surnud","1300":"1300","1299":"1299","1385":"1385","1285":"1285","1280":"1280","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Northumberland, England, United Kingdom":"Northumberland, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Bywell St Andrew, Northumberland, England":"Bywell St Andrew, Northumberland, England"},"fi":{"1285–":"1285–Kuollut","1280–Male":"1280–Kuollut","1300–1385":"1300–1385","1285–Female":"1285–Kuollut","1300":"1300","1299":"1299","1385":"1385","1285":"1285","1280":"1280","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Northumberland, England, United Kingdom":"Northumberland, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Bywell St Andrew, Northumberland, England":"Bywell St Andrew, Northumberland, England"},"fr":{"1285–":"1285–Décédée","1280–Male":"1280–Décédé","1300–1385":"1300–1385","1285–Female":"1285–Décédée","1300":"1300","1299":"1299","1385":"1385","1285":"1285","1280":"1280","England":"Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Northumberland, England, United Kingdom":"Northumberland, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Bywell St Andrew, Northumberland, England":"Bywell St Andrew, Northumberland, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Elizabeth Cheney est née en 1285, à Northumberland, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Elle a épousé Robert Fitzralph Lawson en 1299, à Bywell St Andrew, Northumberland, Angleterre. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fils. Elle est décédée à Angleterre, Royaume-Uni."},"de":{"1285–":"1285–Verstorben","1280–Male":"1280–Verstorben","1300–1385":"1300–1385","1285–Female":"1285–Verstorben","1300":"1300","1299":"1299","1385":"1385","1285":"1285","1